ysOowR.defaultMessage:
Method for discounting cash flows for calculation duration 
 Risk Free Curve - Use the treasury curve without a risk premium 
 Risk Curve - Use the yield curve for the appropriate market 
 Z Spread Curve - Continuous Compounding - Risk Free curve plus the Z spread for each security, calculated on a continuous basis 
 Z Spread Curve - Annual Compounding - Risk Free curve plus the Z spread for each security, calculated on an annual compounding basis. Note that this is more expensive computationally. 
 No Discounting - Cash flows are not discounted at all

I99mJx.defaultMessage:
If zero, duration is calculated based on the standard derivative formula (price of cash flow * cash flow amount * tenor summed over tenors). 
 If greater than zero, duration is calculated based on the difference in security prices at delta curves of this amount, divided by twice the delta.

79ofr9.defaultMessage:
Method for calculating modified (constant yield) duration 
 Annual - assumes annual yield compounding 
 Semi-annual - assumes semi-annual yield compounding (Macaulay) 
 Simulation - assumes yield compounding at the simulation frequency 
 Coupon frequency - yield compounding is determined by coupon frequency 
 CBIRC - coupon frequency plus special treatment of single-payment bonds

0ZXVoG.defaultMessage:
Determines if the kernels for Key Rate duration changes during the simulation. 
 If Current Period, the kernels remain the same for the entire simulation. 
 As a security moves towards maturity, the kernels into which the cash flows are allocated move towards the first kernels. 
 If Simulation Start, kernels adjust so that security cash flows remain in the same kernel as the securities progress towards maturity. 
 For example, any zero-coupon bond will have its Key Rate duration kernel remain the same for the entire simulation, even as the Key Rate duration measure itself progresses towards zero. 
 If the security started in the fifth kernel at the start of the simulation, it remains there throughout the simulation. 
 Note that for the Simulation Start method, the shorter-tenor key rate kernels eventually have no cash flows in them.

uYfGtJ.defaultMessage:
Determines how the kernels for Key Rate are applied to each Key Rate. 
 If Cash Flows, the kernel is multiplied by the cash flow vector to determine the relative importance of the cash flows to the kernel. 
 If Delta, the kernel is multiplied by the interest rate delta to determine the change in interest rates used in finite difference duration calculation. 
 Delta method cannot be used if Delta = 0.0.

Li/NuB.defaultMessage:
By default (disabled), the optimizer will invest excess cash until the maximum tolerance is hit in the order of investment priorities. 
 If this option is enabled, the optimizer will only invest until the target allocation is reached and then move on to the next priority. 
 If the target allocation is 0%, even if the investment priority is highest, no investment will be made to the asset class while this option is enabled. 
 See documentation for more information.

hv1K3O.defaultMessage:
By default (disabled), the optimizer will sell as required until the minimum tolerance is hit in the order of sell priorities. 
 If this option is enabled, the optimizer will only sell until the target allocation is reached and then move on to the next priority. 
 If the target allocation is 100%, even if the sell priority is highest, no selling of the asset class will be performed while this option is enabled. 
 See documentation for more information.

H2cdju.defaultMessage:
By default, the minimum surplus will be in effect immediately. When surplus is below the minimum, a capital infusion is required (causing negative DE). 
 If set to 'When Minimum Surplus is Reached,' the minimum surplus requirement will not be activated until surplus has reached the minimum surplus. 
 If set to 'When Target Surplus is Reached,' the minimum surplus requirement will not be activated until surplus has reached the target surplus. 
 Note that there is a default global minimum surplus of 100% of RBC. A capital infusion always will be required if surplus is below this amount. 
 See documentation for more information.

gfhprq.defaultMessage:
By default, surplus calculations will be performed based on the expected allocation after distributed earnings, new investments, and rebalancing. This is the recommended and most accurate method. 
 If set to 'Start of Period' surplus will based on the asset allocation at the start of the period. 
 If set to 'After Price Returns Before Turnover' surplus will be based on the asset allocation after price returns but before any turnover amounts. 
 If set to 'After Turnover Before Migration' surplus will be based on the asset allocation after price returns and turnover amounts but before any migration is performed. 
 If set to 'After Migration' surplus will be based on the asset allocation after price returns, turnover amounts, and migration. 
 See documentation for more information.

4/Bi3q.defaultMessage:
Defines the point to which we sell assets to pay liability cash outflows. 
 'Never' prohibits the company from selling assets to meet liability cash outflows. Capital would be required from shareholders. 
 Down to Minimum Surplus allows the company to sell assets down to the minimum factor of RBC surplus as defined by the user under 'surplus held.' 
 If the Minimum Factor of RBC is not currently active, assets can be sold down to a limit of 100% of RBC. 
 Down to Target Surplus allows the company to sell assets down to the target factor of RBC surplus as defined by the user under 'surplus held.' 
 See documentation for further information.

pAKkmO.defaultMessage:
When enabled, if the Net Cash Flow is negative (after selling any available assets if the above option is enabled), money will be borrowed at the defined Borrowing Rate. 
 If disabled, a cash infusion would be required causing distributable earnings to be negative.

ZhsEse.defaultMessage:
Defines the point to which we sell assets to pay any outstanding debt. 
 'Never' prohibits the company from selling assets to pay outstanding debt. Debt will accumulate unless there is cash available (from premium, investment income, maturities, turnover, etc.) to make payments. 
 Down to Minimum Surplus allows the company to sell assets down to the minimum factor of RBC surplus as defined by the user under 'surplus held.' 
 If the Minimum Factor of RBC is not currently active, assets can be sold down to a limit of 100% of RBC. 
 Down to Target Surplus allows the company to sell assets down to the target factor of RBC surplus as defined by the user under 'surplus held.' 
 See documentation for further information.
